Bank Churn Prediction¶

Objective:¶

Given a Bank customer, build a neural network based classifier that can determine whether they will leave or not in the next 6 months

Context:¶

Businesses like banks which provide service have to worry about problem of 'Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Data Description:¶

The case study is from an open-source dataset from Kaggle.The dataset contains 10,000 sample points with 14 distinct features such as CustomerId,CreditScore, Geography, Gender, Age, Tenure, Balance etc.

Link to the Kaggle project site: https://www.kaggle.com/barelydedicated/bank-customer-churn-modeling

GitHub repository URL¶

https://github.com/GreatLearningAIML1/gl-pgp-aiml-uta-intl-apr20-SubratMuruni.git¶

1.5.5 Insights from the Exploratory Data Analysis

  1. The variables are in different scales. So scaling is needed for Artificial Neural Network.
  2. There are three columns RowNumber, CustomerId and Surname which are unique for customers and don't add any value to the model. These columns will be dropped.
  3. Geography and Gender are object type which means these columns will be one-hot encoded.
  4. There are no missing values, duplicate rows and no NaN values,
  5. The Histogram shows that all the variables are not normally distributed.
  6. Plotting boxplot shows that the variables CreditScore and Age have outliers. Given that the number of OUtliers are many, Outliers treatment for these two columns will not be considered during pre-processing to avoid biasing that will change the shape of data.
  7. Checking the skewness of the data indicates that NumOfProducts and HasCrCard are skewed variables.
  8. The heatmap shows that there is very weak correlation between the independent variables.
  9. The Pair plot doesn't indicate any trends amongst data.
  10. In conclusion, exploratory data analysis doesn't reveal much about the data.

6.2 Hyperparameter tuning

The following Hyperparameters will be considered for optimization:

  1. Epochs
  2. Batch Size
  3. Optimizer Function
  4. Learning Rate
  5. Hidden Layer Neurons
  6. Activation Function
  7. Drop Out Rate
  8. Momentum
  9. Weight Initialization

    # create model
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(12, input_dim=11, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

6.2.6 Tune dropout regularization

In [90]:
from keras.layers import Dropout
from keras.constraints import maxnorm

# Function to create model, required for KerasClassifier
def create_model(dropout_rate=0.0, weight_constraint=0):
    # create model
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(12, input_dim=11, kernel_initializer='uniform', activation='linear', kernel_constraint=maxnorm(weight_constraint)))
    model.add(Dropout(dropout_rate))
    model.add(Dense(1, kernel_initializer='uniform', activation='sigmoid'))
    # Compile model
    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

# fix random seed for reproducibility
seed = 7
np.random.seed(seed)

# create model
model = KerasClassifier(build_fn=create_model, epochs=100, batch_size=10, verbose=0)
# define the grid search parameters

# Function to create model, required for KerasClassifier
def create_model(neurons=1):
    # create model
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(neurons, input_dim=11, kernel_initializer='uniform', activation='linear', kernel_constraint=maxnorm(4)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(Dense(1, kernel_initializer='uniform', activation='sigmoid'))
    # Compile model
    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

# fix random seed for reproducibility
seed = 7
np.random.seed(seed)

# create model
model = KerasClassifier(build_fn=create_model, epochs=100, batch_size=10, verbose=0)
# define the grid search parameters
neurons = [1,3, 5, 6, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, ]
param_grid = dict(neurons=neurons)

    cm = confusion_matrix(actual,predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm,annot=True, linewidth=0.05, fmt='.2f', xticklabels=[0,1], yticklabels=[0,1])
    plt.ylabel('observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

8.5 Conclusion

In [145]:
# print the metrics for both base model and final model
dfMetrics
Out[145]:
Model Accuracy Recall Precision F1 Score
0 Base ANN 0.8615 0.465649 0.732000 0.569207
0 Final ANN 0.8400 0.284987 0.741722 0.411765


  1. The base model is an overfit model and the final model is a generalized model. The final model will do better in production as compared to the base model.
  2. The final model has 1 hidden layer, which will be a significant factor in deploying in production to avoid larger computational time.
  3. The base model gives slightly improved accuracy score compared to the final model
  4. @ 0.5 Threshold, the base model has a better recall than the final model but slightly low precision
  5. The false negatives (FN) for the final model is higher that the base model. What it means is, the model predicted that the customers will not churn (Leave the bank) but they left the bank.
  6. The objective of the model should be to predict with high recall value for the bank churn prediction. The final model though generalized in characteristic, has low recall.
  7. Upsampling the dataset using SMOTE didn't improve the predictive power of the model. So, Upsampling as a strategy is not fruitful for this dataset.
  8. Since the dataset is an imbalance dataset, a threshold other than 0.5 should be considered. In section-8.4 I have shown that with a threshold of 0.25, the recall of the model can be improved significantly. What it would mean is, any strategy to retain customers of the bank may go to a large number of customers who are not at risk of churn. Hence the communication has to be slightly generic in nature.
